{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 09:42:31.887246", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Anomaly detected: End-to-end IP connectivity from/to pc_0_0 is broken. The fabric control plane is healthy (all EBGP adjacencies up and correct routes installed). pc_0_1 and its leaf are operating normally.\n- Fault localization: The failure is localized to host pc_0_0 at the edge (host-to-leaf segment).\n- Root cause: A misconfigured local firewall rule on pc_0_0 drops virtually all outbound IP packets, preventing both host-originated traffic and ICMP replies to inbound probes. This causes apparent “link up + ARP ok + IP dead” symptoms.\n\nObserved symptoms and tests\n- Host-to-host reachability:\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: ping timed out.\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: ping timed out.\n- Host-to-gateway reachability:\n  - pc_0_1 -> 10.0.1.1 (leaf_router_0_1): success (0% loss, sub-ms RTT).\n  - pc_0_0 -> 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0): 100% loss.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 -> 10.0.1.2 (pc_0_1): success (0% loss).\n  - leaf_router_0_0 -> 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0): 100% loss.\n- L2 and ARP state on the problematic segment (pc_0_0 <-> leaf_router_0_0):\n  - Links up on both ends (ethtool shows link detected: yes).\n  - ARP resolution present in both directions:\n    - pc_0_0 ip neigh: 10.0.0.1 lladdr 2e:b4:ea:49:8e:14 STALE.\n    - leaf_router_0_0 ip neigh/arp: 10.0.0.2 lladdr d6:97:7f:b5:56:6e present.\n  - Interface counters indicate almost no IP traffic leaves pc_0_0:\n    - pc_0_0 eth0: RX 10 packets, TX 2 packets (suggests only ARP activity, not IP).\n    - leaf_router_0_0 eth2: RX 2 packets, TX 10 packets (leaf is sending but host not replying).\n- Firewall on pc_0_0:\n  - iptables:\n    - Policies: INPUT ACCEPT, FORWARD ACCEPT, OUTPUT ACCEPT.\n    - Rule present: -A OUTPUT -m length --length 10:65535 -j DROP.\n    - Effect: Drops essentially all outbound IP packets (normal IPv4 packets are > 10 bytes), including ICMP echo requests and echo replies.\n  - sysctl icmp_echo_ignore_all = 0 (not suppressing ICMP itself).\n- Firewall on routers:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 iptables: default ACCEPT, no blocking rules.\n- Routing/control plane:\n  - All EBGP adjacencies up across leaves, spines, and super-spine.\n  - Each leaf advertises its directly connected /24; all core devices have routes installed:\n    - leaf_router_0_0: C 10.0.0.0/24, B 10.0.1.0/24 via spine (172.16.0.4).\n    - leaf_router_0_1: C 10.0.1.0/24, B 10.0.0.0/24 via spine (172.16.0.6).\n    - spine routers: BGP routes for both /24s present.\n    - super-spine: both /24s present via a spine.\n  - Minor asymmetry observed: spine_router_0_1 shows 0 PfxRcd from super_spine_router_0, while spine_router_0_0 receives 2. This does not affect current reachability because spines learn both /24s directly from leaves. Not causative for the host-to-leaf failure.\n\nAssessment of network health\n- Fabric control plane: Healthy. EBGP sessions established throughout, prefixes propagated and installed as expected.\n- Data plane within fabric: No evidence of impairment; routes point to correct next hops; one leaf-to-host segment (pc_0_0 side) exhibits L3 failure due to host firewall, not the fabric.\n- Edge segments:\n  - Pod 0, leaf_router_0_1 <-> pc_0_1: Healthy (bidirectional ICMP OK).\n  - Pod 0, leaf_router_0_0 <-> pc_0_0: ARP and link are up but IPv4 traffic fails due to host-side egress filtering.\n\nFault localization\n- Faulty device: pc_0_0.\n- Faulty function: Local packet filtering (iptables) on OUTPUT chain.\n- Affected scope: All IP traffic originating from or requiring pc_0_0 to transmit at L3 (including ICMP echo requests and replies). This breaks pc_0_0 -> default gateway, and prevents replies to leaf-originated probes and to pc_0_1.\n\nRoot cause\n- Misconfigured firewall rule on pc_0_0: iptables OUTPUT rule drops all packets with length 10–65535 bytes, effectively blocking all normal IPv4 traffic. ARP is unaffected (L2), which explains correct neighbor entries but complete failure of IP reachability.\n\nSupporting evidence (key excerpts)\n- pc_0_0 iptables: -A OUTPUT -m length --length 10:65535 -j DROP\n- pc_0_0 -> 10.0.0.1: 100% loss; leaf_router_0_0 -> 10.0.0.2: 100% loss.\n- pc_0_1 -> 10.0.1.1 and leaf_router_0_1 -> 10.0.1.2: both succeed, proving leaf0_1/pc_0_1 segment healthy.\n- ARP present on pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0; link detected on both ends; pc_0_0 eth0 TX only 2 packets, indicating IP frames are being filtered before egress.\n\nAdditional notes\n- BGP minor inconsistency: spine_router_0_1 receives 0 prefixes from the super-spine while spine_router_0_0 receives 2. This appears non-impacting in the current single-pod scenario but is noted for completeness.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12417, "output_tokens": 4663, "total_tokens": 17080, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12160}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3264}}}
